 for bestpractices and # User Management (Admin)

## Overview
This prompt enables the AI development tool to build a robust, scalable Admin experience for user management and platform governance. It covers a dedicated User Management (Admin) page (invite, manage roles, deactivate/reactivate, audit logs), an Admin Controls & Monitoring module (user management, ingestion replays, system health), and an Admin Dashboard (subscription billing overview and platform analytics). The implementation must be resilient, accessible, secure, and aligned with the provided design system and runtime-safety requirements. All code must guard against null/undefined values before calling array methods, use data ?? [] for Supabase results, initialize React state for arrays/objects with proper defaults, validate API responses, and prefer optional chaining.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- The User Management (Admin) page is an administrative interface to manage platform users. It enables inviting new users, assigning and editing roles, deactivating/reactivating user accounts, and viewing audit logs of sign-ins and sensitive actions.

Goals:
- Provide a single, coherent admin surface to manage users efficiently, with fast search/filter, bulk actions, and audit traceability.
- Ensure security with role-based access controls, activity auditing, and proper validation of all inputs.
- Integrate with Admin Controls & Monitoring to expose ingestion replays and system health signals where relevant to admins.
- Feed into the Admin Dashboard for subscription billing overview and analytics by providing relevant user and activity metrics.

Connected features:
- Admin Controls & Monitoring: User management, ingestion replays, system health monitoring.
- Admin Dashboard: Admin console for user management, subscription billing overview, platform analytics.

UI elements and how they need to look:
- A list/table of users with search, filters (role, status, team), and bulk actions.
- Invite User modal: fields for email, role, team assignment, and optional metadata.
- Edit User modal: change role, enable/disable toggle, and audit trail display.
- Audit Log Viewer: filters by action type (signin, role change, deactivation/reactivation), date range, and user.
- Visual emphasis on clarity, auditability, and quick actionability with accessible controls.

Visual guidance:
- Warm, calm admin palette with strong typography and readable UI. Prioritize high-contrast text, well-spaced layouts, and accessible controls.

## Components to Build
- UserManagementPage
  - Table/Grid of users with server-paginated data, search, and filters.
  - Bulk actions toolbar (Suspend, Activate, Change Role, Remove).
  - Invite User button opening InviteUserModal.
  - Row actions: Edit (open EditUserModal), Deactivate/Reactivate toggle.
  - Audit Logs panel or tab within page, with filter controls.
- InviteUserModal
  - Form: email (validated), role selection, team assignment, optional notes.
  - Validation: email format, required fields, duplicate invite checks.
  - Submit creates a pending invitation or direct user entry depending on flow.
- EditUserModal
  - Form: role selector, status toggle (Active / Inactive), possibly team reassignment.
  - Validation: role validity, status coherency.
- AuditLogViewer
  - Read-only display of audit entries with search by user, action, date range.
  - Pagination or infinite scroll support.
- AdminControlsPanel (Admin page extension)
  - IngestionReplaysPanel: status, retry/replay controls, recent runs.
  - SystemHealthPanel: CPU/memory/disk health signals, alert indicators.
- AdminDashboardOverview
  - Subcomponents for: User counts, active subscriptions overview, platform analytics tiles (KPIs).
  - Visual tiles with micro-interactions and accessible labels.

Technical details (data model driven)
- User entity fields: id, email, display_name, role, status (Active/Inactive), team_id, created_at, last_login_at, invited_by, audit_log_cursor.
- Team entity: id, name, description.
- Invitation entity: id, email, role, team_id, invited_at, status, token.
- AuditLog entity: id, user_id (subject), action_type (signin, role_change, deactivate, reactivate, invite), target_user_id (if applicable), timestamp, metadata (JSON blob).
- Roles: Admin, Moderator, Support, Viewer (and any organization-specific roles).
- Ingestions and health metrics (AdminControls): ingestion_id, source, status (success, failed, in_progress), retriable boolean, last_attempt_at, health_metrics (JSON).
- Subscription/Billing: plan_name, status, renewal_date, seats, revenue, metrics.

Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Framework: React with TypeScript (recommended for type safety).
- State management: useState and useEffect for page-level state; consider useReducer for complex flows; avoid undefined/null array states.
- Accessibility: ensure aria-labels, focus management when modals open, keyboard navigability.
- UI components:
  - DataTable component with:
    - Sorting, filtering, pagination, and client-side guards for null values.
  - Modal components (InviteUserModal, EditUserModal) with focus trapping and proper aria attributes.
  - Form controls: select, input, toggle switch, badges for statuses, and validated inputs.
  - AuditLogViewer with date range picker and action-type filters.
  - Spinners/empty states with accessible messaging.
  - Badges: role, status, activity states.
- Runtime safety:
  - All API data usage follows data ?? [] defaults, Array.isArray checks, and safe mappings.
  - Never call .map/.filter/.reduce on values that could be null/undefined; use (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
  - Initialize arrays in useState: const [users, setUsers] = useState<User[]>([]);
  - Validate API responses: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [];
  - Use optional chaining for nested API payloads: data?.user?.email, etc.
  - Destructure with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}.
- API integrations (frontend layer):
  - Endpoints assumed:
    - GET /admin/users?filters... (returns { data: User[], count: number } or { data: null, count: 0 })
    - POST /admin/users/invite (body: { email, role, teamId, invitedBy })
    - PUT /admin/users/:id (body: { role?, status? })
    - GET /admin/audit-logs?userId&action&from&to (returns { data: AuditLog[] })
    - GET /admin/ingestions/replays (for ingestion replays)
    - GET /admin/health (system health metrics)
  - All response handlers guard against nulls and use data ?? [] patterns.
  - Ensure idempotent operations for invites and role changes; implement optimistic UI updates with rollback on error.
- Validation:
  - Email format validation on Invite modal.
  - Role and team selections required when inviting.
  - Ensure no duplicate invites for the same email in a short time window (local/temporary guard or server-side check).

### Backend
- API endpoints (Express/NestJS/Any) with TypeScript definitions:
  - GET /admin/users
    - Query params: search, role, status, teamId, page, pageSize
    - Response: { data: User[], count: number } | { data: null, count: 0 }
  - POST /admin/users/invite
    - Body: { email, role, teamId }
    - Behavior: create Invitation, optionally create user placeholder; send invitation email; idempotent checks.
  - PUT /admin/users/:id
    - Body: { role?, status? }
    - Behavior: update user role/status; emit audit log entry.
  - GET /admin/audit-logs
    - Query: userId, actionType, from, to, limit, offset
    - Response: { data: AuditLog[], count: number }
  - GET /admin/ingestions/replays
    - Response: { data: IngestionReplay[], count }
  - GET /admin/health
    - Response: { status: string, metrics: HealthMetrics }
- Database schema (PostgreSQL or your DB):
  - users(id PK, email unique, display_name, role, status, team_id FK, created_at, last_login_at, invited_by)
  - teams(id PK, name)
  - invitations(id PK, email, role, team_id FK, invited_at, status, token)
  - audit_logs(id PK, user_id FK NULLABLE, action_type, target_user_id, timestamp, metadata JSONB)
  - ingestion_replays(id PK, source, status, last_attempt_at, details JSONB)
  - system_health(metrics JSONB, checked_at)
  - subscriptions(plan_name, status, renewal_date, seats, revenue)
- Security:
  - Ensure RBAC: only admins can access admin endpoints.
  - Validate inputs server-side; sanitize emails and roles.
  - Log sensitive actions to AuditLog (invite, role change, deactivate/reactivate).
- Validation:
  - Validate that user updates do not set invalid roles.
  - Ensure team_id exists or is null based on business rules.
  - Ensure invitations are rate-limited per email.

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - Admin User Management page fetches users via GET /admin/users with filters.
  - Invite action calls POST /admin/users/invite; on success, refresh user list and add audit entry.
  - Edit action calls PUT /admin/users/:id; on success, refresh user list and log audit event.
  - Audit Logs panel fetches via GET /admin/audit-logs with user filters; reflects changes in UI in near real-time via polling or WebSocket if available.
  - Admin Controls panels fetch ingestion replays and health data; present in AdminControlsPanel.
  - Admin Dashboard consumes relevant data from the subscriptions and analytics endpoints to display billing and platform KPIs.
- State synchronization:
  - After mutations (invite/modify), trigger optimistic UI updates with rollback on error.
  - Centralize error handling with user-friendly messages and retry options.
- Data normalization:
  - Normalize API responses to consistent shapes; always guard against missing fields.
  - Use utility functions to map raw API data into UI-friendly types (e.g., mapUser, mapAuditLog).

## User Experience Flow
1) Admin lands on the User Management (Admin) page.
2) They see a header with the page title, search bar, and filters (role, status, team) and an Invite User button.
3) Admin uses search or filters to locate a user; the results appear in a paginated table with columns: Email, Name, Role, Team, Status, Created At, Last Login, Actions.
4) Admin clicks Invite User to open InviteUserModal:
   - Enters email, selects role, selects team, optionally adds notes.
   - Validates inputs; submits.
   - On success: shows a toast, refreshes the user list, logs an audit entry, and sends an invitation email.
5) Admin clicks Edit on a user row to open EditUserModal:
   - Adjusts role or toggles Active/Inactive status; optionally reassigns team.
   - Confirms changes; submits.
   - On success: shows a toast, refreshes list, logs audit entry.
6) Admin uses Audit Logs panel to filter by action, user, date range; views a list of logs with timestamp, action, involved users, and metadata.
7) Admin navigates to Admin Controls & Monitoring tabs to review Ingestion Replays (retry/replay) and System Health metrics.
8) Admin returns to Admin Dashboard to review Subscription Billing Overview and Platform Analytics tiles; metrics refresh automatically or on demand.
9) All actions produce accessible, auditable traces visible in Audit Logs.

